        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46906",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mabe",
                        "name": "mabe",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (private)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Also on errors reading xml data the libXMLError can be used and for each error an exception can be thrown by using previous argument.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mabe",
                        "name": "mabe",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (private)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-05-29T17:43:18.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-05-29T17:43:18.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/47096",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=matthew",
                        "name": "matthew",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Weier O'Phinney",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Our coding standard frowns on usage of error suppression; it's an expensive operation, and also not friendly with automated tools and debuggers (e.g., ext\/scream will cause load failure, and PHPUnit throws errors when suppression occurs that are often hard to trace).\r\n\r\nI agree that we should update how parse_ini_file is handled on failure, and, per your initial pull request, SimpleXML; however, error suppression should not be part of the solution.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=matthew",
                        "name": "matthew",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Weier O'Phinney",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-06-09T19:18:03.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-06-09T19:18:03.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/47339",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mabe",
                        "name": "mabe",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (private)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi Matthew,\r\n\r\nI'm not 100% the same opinion because of:\r\n - using of a temporarily error handler its a little bit slower than using error suppression with \"@\"\r\n   and a little bit more slower if no error was reported (see attachment)\r\n - using of a temporarily error handler its also a way of error suppression but only another way to do that\r\n - PHPUnit doesn't report suppressed errors\r\n - using of \"@\" and throwing an Exception with the last error is more a rewrite of this error (Error -> Exception) as an real error suppression. Not ?\r\n - only ext\/scream will break here but this extension is a very specific debugging tool which changes the code logic by disabling of \"@\"\r\n   (I don't know other extensions\/tools where this is an issue)\r\n - If we have to create an temporarily error handler on each PHP function which would create an error than we blow up the code extremely\r\n - I found 222 usages of \"@\" within the current library (^[a-z0-9_\\-\\$\\s\\=]\\+@.\\+)\r\n\r\n\r\nOver all I also don't like error suppression but using a temporary error handler is also a way of error suppression\r\nand on PHP there is sometimes no way not using it :(\r\nFor me it should debate from case to case with some points like:\r\n - only use it on internal php functions\r\n - returns the function something to check if an error was triggered\r\n - do something on error (not only suppress it)\r\n - could the function trigger more than one error and if yes use a temporary error handler (or something similar)\r\n   to report all triggered errors\r\n ...\r\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mabe",
                        "name": "mabe",
                        "displayName": "Marc Bennewitz (private)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-07-03T00:38:36.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-07-03T00:38:36.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/47340",
                    "author": {
